Claim:
19
Pregnant people should have the right to choose abortion.
The ability of people to access abortion services, and have control over their own reproduction, is fundamental to achieving gender equality.

If a woman is not allowed to have an abortion, she is not only forced to continue the pregnancy to birth, but also expected by society to support and look after the resulting child for many years to come.

In certain religious households where abstinence is an important virtue, women who get pregnant out of wedlock are shunned. This leaves pregnant women with very little financial and emotional support, while forcing them to be the sole provider for the child.
In a majority of cases, a mother is the primary caregiver of a child and has to invest more time and energy in taking care of the child.
Women often have to sacrifice their careers for childbearing and child-rearing which is not the case with men.
Pregnancy and motherhood have a substantial impact on a woman’s career.

Once women return to work after giving birth, many women face a "motherhood wage penalty,” especially at the bottom of the income spectrum. This means that working mothers encounter systematic disadvantages in pay, perceived competence, and benefits relative to childless women.

The work-effort theory suggests mothers may earn less because they are less productive at work due to the needs of their children leaving them exhausted and distracted, or because they are saving their energy for their "second shift".
Mothers may trade higher wages for “mother-friendly” jobs that are easier to combine with parenting (p. 204).
A study at Cornell University shows that being a mother is proven to be a clear disadvantage when applying for jobs.

When a similar experiment was reproduced in laboratory settings, mothers were offered salaries of around $11,000 less than women without children. Fathers were offered salaries of around $2,000 more. (p. 1316)

Motherhood has a greater impact on a woman’s career prospects than her level of education, according to a study by the Young Women’s Trust. Women with a dependent child are six times more likely to be economically inactive than those without children (p. 4).
This is mainly due to patriarchal oppression, not the demands of motherhood. It is possible to employ and educate mothers while giving them ample maternity leave, equal pay, and quality healthcare.

A woman who gets pregnant, gives birth, and finds someone to adopt the child does not end up with a dependent child. However, having to raise a dependent child is what caused negative career outcomes for the women, not pregnancy by itself.
In most Western countries, there are legal measures that allow women to retain their employment status and forbid discrimination based on having children.
Taking maternity leave inherently stalls one's career, even if there is not explicit discrimination.
Studies suggest that among men with equivalent resumes, fathers are more likely to receive call-backs and higher wage offers than are childless men.
This is a problem with culture and employment, not childbearing.

It is false to suggest that future educational and career goals must be abandoned when one becomes pregnant. With the choice of adoption and the many support programs which exist today, young women or teens can postpone their educational plans but still achieve them.
Many fathers leave their children behind, leaving the mothers to care for them on their own.
Father absence is a cultural problem in its own right, but no reason to preemptively abort.
What is true for the majority may not apply in every case - a father may wish to take on the role of a child's primary caregiver.
The introduction of paternity leave in some countries has seen a rise in the number of men taking time off work to raise their children (p. 16).
There are increasing numbers of fathers who wish to be stay at home parents.
Fathers are held financially responsible for their children. It is not only mothers who are forced to take care of the unwanted children.
Fathers have to help fund and support the child until they are no longer a dependent, usually 18 years, which would add to the emotional burden on the father and the father's family.
Only 50% of single parents have a child support agreement in place with the other parent of their child in the US, which shows that it is difficult to enforce financial responsibility.
Society is better off if women only have the children they want and can raise well.

Denying women the right to terminate pregnancies at an early stage implies that giving birth to children is the most important thing a woman will ever do; that her ability to give birth trumps any other contribution to society she could possibly make.
Denying women access to safe, legal abortion in the interests of the embryo values the woman’s actual life less than the potential life of the embryo.
Many women who have made great contributions to society have done so as mothers.
Denial of the right to terminate a pregnancy says nothing about the relative importance of giving birth.
Abortion can help prevent the numerous financial issues that come from having an unplanned pregnancy.
Even if women are out of high school, unwanted pregnancy can force them to leave their jobs, furthering inequality in the workforce.
Women often have to sacrifice their careers for childbearing and child-rearing which is not the case with men.
Studies suggest that among men with equivalent resumes, fathers are more likely to receive call-backs and higher wage offers than are childless men.
Pregnancy and motherhood have a substantial impact on a woman’s career.
A study at Cornell University shows that being a mother is proven to be a clear disadvantage when applying for jobs.

When a similar experiment was reproduced in laboratory settings, mothers were offered salaries of around $11,000 less than women without children. Fathers were offered salaries of around $2,000 more. (p. 1316)

Motherhood has a greater impact on a woman’s career prospects than her level of education, according to a study by the Young Women’s Trust. Women with a dependent child are six times more likely to be economically inactive than those without children (p. 4).
This is mainly due to patriarchal oppression, not the demands of motherhood. It is possible to employ and educate mothers while giving them ample maternity leave, equal pay, and quality healthcare.

Once women return to work after giving birth, many women face a "motherhood wage penalty,” especially at the bottom of the income spectrum. This means that working mothers encounter systematic disadvantages in pay, perceived competence, and benefits relative to childless women.

The work-effort theory suggests mothers may earn less because they are less productive at work due to the needs of their children leaving them exhausted and distracted, or because they are saving their energy for their "second shift".
Mothers may trade higher wages for “mother-friendly” jobs that are easier to combine with parenting (p. 204).
In most Western countries, there are legal measures that allow women to retain their employment status and forbid discrimination based on having children.
Taking maternity leave inherently stalls one's career, even if there is not explicit discrimination.

A woman who gets pregnant, gives birth, and finds someone to adopt the child does not end up with a dependent child. However, having to raise a dependent child is what caused negative career outcomes for the women, not pregnancy by itself.

It is false to suggest that future educational and career goals must be abandoned when one becomes pregnant. With the choice of adoption and the many support programs which exist today, young women or teens can postpone their educational plans but still achieve them.
This is a problem with culture and employment, not childbearing.

Preference for equality in the workforce is not a satisfactory reason for abortion.  Many childless women are treated unequally in the workforce as it is.  We can strive for equality whilst also supporting childbearing.

One of the reasons for unequal treatment of women in the workforce is the assumption that they will get pregnant and leave their job any time. If women are denied the option to terminate unwanted pregnancies, this further fuels such assumptions and encourages discrimination in the workplace.
The option to have an abortion gives women more autonomy over their careers, as it allows them to plan ahead and discuss maternity leave with their employers before actually needing it.
Giving women the right to have an abortion if they want to does not oppose or contradict support for childbearing. Allowing women a choice does not make anything compulsory.
When women cannot afford to raise their children they are forced to go on welfare, which is a cost to everyone.

Women who are denied abortions and instead give birth are 3.77 times more likely to be in poverty and 6.26 times more likely to be on public assistance 6 months after denial than women who received abortions. They are also more likely to be in poverty and remain on public assistance for 4 years after denial of abortion (pp. 411-412).
Society is best when we look out for others. Supporting people who need it through welfare is not necessarily a bad thing.
A case could be made that it would be better to have our tax dollars contributed to welfare, than have that same money be contributed to abortion.
Many women who become pregnant are still in high school and are forced to drop out.
Governments should provide support to families to ensure that abortion is not the only option and that these financial issues are not significant.

There is evidence to suggest that the Roe v. Wade decision to legalize abortion in 1978 was responsible for the dramatic decrease in violent crime the United States experienced through at least 1999 (p. 414).
There is evidence from Canada, Australia, and Romania that also supports the hypothesis that abortion reduces crime.

Five US states legalised abortion three years before Roe v. Wade. Crime started falling three years earlier in these states, with property crime (committed by younger people) falling before violent crime.
The ends do not justify the means. Using an immoral act (abortion) to justify a good (improved crime rates) is unethical.
Individuals contribute to society in numerous different ways, and even children that are not wanted or raised well may make valuable contributions that mean society is better off.
It is possible to provide more education and access to resources and contraception to reduce the number of unwanted pregnancies without relying on abortion.

Even if society is better in some ways if women only have the children they want, this is not enough to justify killing the children. Otherwise, women would be permitted kill toddlers they are currently raising but don't want.
Better access to contraception and improved sexual education would reduce the risk of unplanned pregnancies.
Abortion is a band-aid solution to systemic issues in society. While it may need to remain legal, it does nothing to address the reasons behind unwanted pregnancy.

Access to contraception will not help when many religious and cultural circles demand abstinence. Young women may have access to contraception but choose not to carry or use it because they are at a higher risk of being caught and punished for being sexually active.

A lot of those circles also ban abortion, so the justification of abortion by citing these situations is a fallacy. They already stigmatise abortion and demand carrying to full term, so they are an irrelevant factor in the discussion.
Abortion would not disappear no matter how accessible birth control and adoption becomes.

Sweden's abortion statistics show that abortions will still happen, even in spite of the fact that many parts of the country provide heavily subsidised birth control for women up to their mid-twenties, free condoms at clinics, and free abortions up to 25-26.
The issue is that these resources are not properly allocated or presented to the populace. Women should not be made to suffer because of a failure of government.

In many countries without strong state support for family planning services, doctors might be more inclined towards the lucrative work of performing abortions over the prescription of birth control - as was the case in Romania throughout the 1990s.

The possibility of doctors being corrupt and state not having strong family planning services support are not variables that should come into play when deciding general legality of abortion. They circumvent the fundamental "right to abortion" issue by blaming external factors.
Abortion worsens gender inequality.

Abortion is an instrument of the patriarchy. It's a way men can use women as objects of sexual pleasure and escape the responsibilities of fatherhood. Sometimes women may decide to get an abortion because of pressure or threats from the father.
A survey of 1000 women found 74% felt pressured by others while 30% chose abortion because they feared losing their man.

A survey of 1209 abortion patients found that fewer than 1% had abortions primarily because someone else insisted. Thus, in the majority of cases women would have their choice taken away by abortion being illegal, not legal.

Considering this topic regards whether the woman has the right to choose to terminate life, and not whether the father has any say, then support of the woman's right alone to choose is not a step for gender equality, but rather increases gender inequality.
In many countries, girls are more likely to be aborted, resulting in a disproportionate male-to-female ratio.
In India, approximately 10 million girls were aborted between 1991 and 2011, which has led to there being 914 girls to every 1000 boys by 2011.
A study found that some Indian-born immigrants in Canada are electively aborting female fetuses if they have already had two daughters.
The incidence of this is low, and the practice is likely to go away on its own as immigrants become settled.

A study found that in Indian families where the firstborn was a girl, the second child was unnaturally likely to be a boy, whereas if the firstborn was a boy, sex ratios among subsequent children were normal.
The study also found that second boys were not aborted, only second girls.
This says more about gender equality than about the right of abortion. If there is a preferred gender, then that is the issue, not the abortion.
When women are more likely to be aborted, this normalizes a narrative that women's lives are less important.
In China, sons are often seen as more desirable. This is particularly the case in rural areas where sons are valued because of their ability to perform manual and agricultural work.
These narratives are being challenged and measures are being taken to prevent sex-selective abortions.
This argument is easily separated from the larger argument by making it illegal to determine the sex of the fetus in these countries as is the case in countries like India already.

This approach undermines the freedom of couples to properly plan for their baby. There are legitimate medical and social reasons to find out the baby's sex ahead of time (e.g. preparing older siblings, intersex children, pure curiosity) that do not involve sex-based abortion. This unfairly limits all couple's options to prevent some couples from discriminatory abortions.
Late undesired pregnancy impedes the woman of performing her professional activities for a considerable period of time, thus, making her dependent on her partner, institutions and her family.
There are many reasons a woman may not be equipped to or want to raise a child. In these cases, it is important that she is able to choose abortion.

Pregnancy and parenthood are very expensive and time consuming. Many women who get abortions are already mothers, and they want to provide the best care they can to their existing children, financially, emotionally, and physically. This should be their choice.
A study by University of California shows that existing children of women denied an abortion have 4 percentage point lower scores across all six domains of child development.
Abortion can have a negative effect on living children.

Post-abortal women report that their ability to respond to the remaining or future child(ren) can be manifested in several ways: a feeling of emotional numbness which leads to a lack of bonding, acting out of hostility and anger which can result in child abuse, and considering future children as “replacement children” who become overindulged (p. 11).

After abortion, “replacement” children may find themselves the object of obsessive parenting styles of post-abortal parents who focus inordinate time, affection, or material goods on them. Parents may attempt to replace the lost child with a “wanted” child soon after the abortion. This can be detrimental to a child's development and behavior (p. 13).
A vasectomy or tubal ligation would be adequate and less harmful in this scenario.

Some hospitals do not perform vasectomies or tubal ligations on religious grounds. (e.g. Many Catholic hospitals in Canada and the United States have not performed these services in the recent past, see links.) Therefore, this point only applies if these services are readily available and not themselves disallowed.

If the fetus is already a child, then it follows from your argument that one should be able to terminate one's offspring to better provide for the rest. This is immoral, and therefore, abortion for the reasons you presented is immoral.
A woman might feel that her home does not provide a safe environment for a child.
Many entire neighborhoods are not safe for raising a child.

Women in physically violent and abusive relationships are likely to stay tethered to abusive partners when they are unable to terminate unwanted pregnancies. This puts both the women and their children at increased risk of violence.

Intimate partner violence is common among women having abortions, with between 6% and 22% reporting recent violence from an intimate partner. Concern about violence is a reason some pregnant women decide to terminate their pregnancies as they do not wish to expose children to violence.
Governments have processes to remove children from these types of situations. This service alongside adoption, imprisonment, and help from family members saves countless children from harm.
For example, in the United States, there are the Child Protective Services.

It would be in the state's interest to have as few children taken away from their parents by Child Protective Services as possible. Denying these abortions would mean significant increases in public spending for various social care services.
In the long term, this would cause more trouble than allowing a woman to have an abortion when she wants one.
Abortion and birth control are fiscally responsible. Spending $235 million on family planning would save $1.32 billion.

Women who are denied abortions and instead give birth are 3.77 times more likely to be in poverty and 6.26 times more likely to be on public assistance 6 months after denial than women who received abortions. They are also more likely to be in poverty and remain on public assistance for 4 years after denial of abortion (pp. 411-412).
This source speaks only of birth control and spending money on contraceptive services being fiscally responsible, not abortion.

Child protective services takes children away from parents, which does not help the women seeking a safe environment and the intervention of the Child Protection Service may make that environment even worse.
Adoption does not guarantee a safe life for children.
State institutions are bad at properly assessing whether or not the environment of foster homes are safe.
State institutions are bad at properly assessing whether or not the environment of foster homes are safe.
The screening process is only as good as the person who makes the assessment and the level of stress or workload they may be facing.
In New York, the 40% turnover in caseworkers is testament to the heavy workload they face, which could reflect in the quality of their work.

The average foster care social worker is paid $47,372 annually. This is substantially less than other working professionals such as IT Managers ($79,584) or HR managers ($73,474). These workers are then forced to make tough decisions and deal with difficult situations on a day to day basis.
Private foster care agencies have allowed criminals and registered sex offenders to acquire licenses and adopt foster children. This has led to neglect, sexual abuse and murders of children.

A caseworker in one such agency reported that three girls were happy and healthy in their foster home when in fact they had been dead for three months. This is indicative of the sheer ineptitude of many foster care agencies.

Many LGBTQ children in foster homes suffer abuse. As a result, in the US, 56% spent some time homeless because they believed they were safer on the streets than they were in their foster homes (p. 5).
In the UK, there is legislation underpinning the work of fostering agencies, requiring them to ensure children are safeguarded and protected from significant harm (p. 14).
Policies are generally in place to ensure foster homes are safe, including annual reviews.
Most children would probably prefer adoption to abortion if given a choice, even if adoption and foster care are not perfect.
It remains the fact that many of adoptees appreciate the fact that they are alive. 7.6 percent of adoptees trying to commit suicide, as stated in this study, are still a small minority.
Even children who undergo horrific abuse still have a strong will to survive, so it is reasonable that the vast majority of children would prefer even the worst forms of adoption to abortion.

Some children do overcome the hardships of being unwanted and/or abused, some don't. Suicide rates among youths in foster care are among the highest in the United States. To claim the "vast majority" of children would prefer pain, lack of love, disconnectedness and dim future prospects over having not been born at all is supported by unfounded hope alone.
It is not possible to infer the preferences of an entity that lacks that the mental architecture to carry a preference.
The woman and her doctor are in the best position to make such a consequential decision.
It is reasonable to assume that a late-stage fetus (e.g. 8 months) is no less capable of having a preference than a newborn.
This is likely true. A newborn baby has no capability of weighing the benefits and detriments of life or no life. It's a philosophical conundrum even deep-thinking philosophers struggle with.

There are numerous physiological changes that occur at birth, including shifting the blood flow to pass through the lungs. Previous to birth, a fully conscious individual would suffer from sensory deprivation. Therefore it is probable that some physiological change occurs that ignites consciousness.
Some people are now attempting to sue their parents for recklessly bringing them into the world, as the parents knew of defects and circumstances that handicapped them.
This area of law is as yet undeveloped but test cases are forming. This shows that some people don't appreciate having been allowed to be born into adverse conditions.
These are still a small minority of people. One cannot assume their child will become one of them.

Birth doesn't guarantee a safe life for children. Expecting parents who want a child can't even guarantee a safe life for children. Abortion, however, guarantees that the child will not have a safe life, or a life at all.
Abortion guarantees a child will not have an unsafe or miserable life. To prevent a likely painful and difficult life can be a blessing.

The trend described in the source also appears to hold for positive, healthy relationships. The benefits caused by healthy relationships lasting longer help outweigh any negative effects from bad relationships going longer than they should.
Optimal conditions for child-rearing are relatively rare. Children raised in unsafe environments can survive and thrive despite risk factors.

Indeed, children can survive in threatening and abusive environments where their future prospects in life are dim. However, it would be irresponsible to put children through such life trauma when we can spare them of it.

It's neglectful, indeed possibly mean-spirited, to bring an unloved child into the world only to suffer a difficult, challenging and, likely, painful life when a mother could be sympathetic to a would-be child's future brutal life and prevent it.
Life begins at conception. Abortion therefore violates the rights to life and bodily autonomy of the fetus.
Biological facts indicate that fetuses are human.
Human embryos autonomously direct their own development after conception, even when they are not in their mothers’ wombs.
This is not enough to define embryos as complete humans worthy of every human right.

Human development is a continuum, except at conception and at birth, which are the only possible candidates for the beginning of personhood. Many people agree that late-term fetuses are persons, meaning that personhood must begin at conception.
There is a discontinuity. At first the fetus is unable to survive on its own outside the body of the mother. Then at some point the baby is able to survive on its own.

'At some point' is not a true discontinuity anymore than a bird flying at some point or a joey leaving the pouch at some point is. It is just a mark of growth, not a discontinuous stage like a larva or chrysalis would be.
Survival is a poor criteria to determine the beginning of a human life. Newborns cannot survive on their own either.
It is not entirely clear at what stage during the pregnancy this occurs, making it difficult to draw a line about when abortion would and would not be acceptable based on this.
There is no discontinuity in human development between adolescence and adulthood, yet we still recognize them as distinct phases of life. There's no rule saying a phase change requires discontinuity.

It is recognized that embryo, fetus and child are distinct phases of life, exactly like adolescence and adulthood are. The point is that human life is equaly valuable in all of its phases; old age, adulthood, adolescence, childhood, newborn, fetus, embryo.
This continuity begins with sperm and egg, which would make masturbation similar to abortion.
There is no scientific basis to give personhood to the gametes of any of the two sexes. Neither of them is a totipotent cell, with the potentiality to become human beings on their own.

A sperm plus an egg would give rise to such a totipotent cell. If such a cell is of moral value, it stands to reason that what gives rise to it is also of moral value. In that case, destroying or preventing the development of a sperm plus egg would be as immoral as destroying or preventing the development of a zygote or fetus.

Masturbation generally does not include both eggs and sperms present simultaneously, and by most definitions does not include fertilization. There is a distinct beginning of continuity with fertilization.
There is a big jump between sperm cells and a baby with formed organs inside a mothers womb not yet able to live on its own.
Biology textbooks are consistent that the lifecycle of a genetically distinct human organism begins at conception.
The human life cycle begins at fertilization, when an egg cell inside a woman and a sperm cell from a man fuse to form a one-celled zygote.

Before fertilization, the exact same components are present as an egg and sperm. If destroying a zygote is immoral, likewise the destruction of the egg and/or the sperm that would produce it would be immoral. But the destruction of the egg or sperm is not immoral, and so destroying a zygote wouldn't be immoral.
Biology does not treat mother and fetus as one organism, but two separate and distinct human organisms.
The unborn human has its DNA set from conception. While similar to the mother's and father's due to inherited chromosomes and genetic traits, the DNA is not the same as the mother's.
DNA is not set but changes over time.

Suppose the fetus was not genetically unique from its mother (something which is possible), that would have no bearing on the question as to whether abortion was moral or not. Thus, genetic uniqueness is an irrelevant criterion when deciding the morality of abortion.

While present in the mother's body, the fertilized egg is not part of the body and never becomes part of the mother's body. It travels through the fallopian tube entirely independent of the mother's nutrients until it attaches via placenta into the womb.

A fertilized egg becomes a fetus which is physically connected to the mother's body via the umbilical cord; it is dependent on her body for nutrients, and cannot sustain its own life, therefore it is not yet separate from her body but an extension of it.
Tonsils and tumors are genetically human, yet it is not immoral to excise and destroy them. Thus, being genetically human is not sufficient.
Having different DNA does not mean it is a separate and valid life by any means. Bacteria and some cancers have different DNA and we commonly remove it when it is growing unwanted in the human body.
Tonsils and tumors are not an entire human organism, just a part. The argument is that it is immoral to destroy an entire human organism, which a baby is.

The majority of biology textbooks used to use creationism to describe the world's history and omitted evolution. The fact that biology textbooks are consistent in how they describe conception is not a reason we should believe in that description.
Just because biology textbooks got something wrong in the past doesn't mean that their views on embryology are wrong now.
When a biology textbook says that DNA has a double helix structure, it would make little sense to doubt that just because other textbooks used to teach creationism.
Being a biological human being is legally and morally distinct from being a person with the rights and responsibilities ascribed to legal personhood.
Even if a fetus is considered human, it does not have a 'right to life' as it does not qualify for the status of 'personhood.'
Fetuses are yet to become citizens of the state since they are unborn and therefore have no rights or protection under common law.

Citizenship is irrelevant to the legality and morality of the act. Non-citizens enjoy the protection of the law just as much as citizens do. It is not legal to kill a non-citizen any more than it is to kill a citizen (p. 5).

A human being requires a functional brain, wherein the mind resides. During pregnancy the brain doesn't even start to form until six weeks after conception when the neural tube closes, and the brain does not become functional until "around the time a full-term baby is born".
This is why brain death is generally the medical definition of death.
Being a human being does not require a functional brain because anencephalic infants do not have a functional brain, but they are still human beings.
A fetus is not self aware, conscious, or able to feel pain.
It is not until 28-30 weeks into the pregnancy that the fetus starts to feel pain. A woman should have the right to an abortion, as long as it's before that time.
Fetuses can feel pain well before that.

A study concludes that from the 15th week of gestation onward, “the fetus is extremely sensitive to painful stimuli," and this should be considered when performing invasive medical procedures on the fetus to prevent suffering.
The support for this argument is a single testimony provided in an article written by an organization prejudiced against abortion.
Killing people is still considered unethical even if the victim doesn't feel pain.
Ethics and morality are subjective and can vary from society to society or even from person to person.

Morals are a set of rules that individuals live by, thus it cannot be suggested that people with different morals are somehow incorrect or wrong. Women should have the right to choose what happens to their body and to live by the morals they choose for themselves.

Saying that “women should always have the right to choose” is a moral judgment, that according to your argument, can not be judged as “correct” or “right.” All laws are codifications of moral judgments, and there are some acts that are universally considered immoral, such as the taking of an innocent human life.

If a society polices for murder, theft, or other crimes considered immoral, then that society finds it ethically acceptable to determine what is a crime, create laws to prohibit that crime, and then police to enforce the law.
These laws may change over time as the society reevaluates and changes, but the fundamental ethics of the society hold that it may create laws based in moral principles and then enforce them.
As with all acts, the morality of abortion varies with the person's context.

In an instance where the pregnant woman's life is at risk and the fetus would not survive on it's own, utilitarianism argues that an abortion would be more ethical than letting both the woman and the fetus die.
The basis of utilitarianism argumentation would be that the overall good of saving the woman's life outweighs any unethical implications of abortions.

Having an abortion for medical reasons makes up less than 1% of all abortions, even lower when the "life of the mother" is in jeopardy. The utilitarian justification for abortion is therefore very, very small.
Statistics regarding the number of abortions due to endangerment of mother's life back this up. Florida, 2015: 0.065%. UK,1968-2011: 0.006%. U.S. estimate: 1%.
It is reasonable to give priority to the mother over the child in extreme cases. However, this does not make voluntary abortions acceptable.

"Less than 1% of all abortions" could be misleading because if between 1970 and 2014, there were "44.5 million legal induced abortions", then there could be 445k abortions that fall in this category. That would be a significant impact to a lot of people.
Abortion would still need to be legal for those cases, as adoption would not solve the issue at hand.
The number of times something happens doesn't always make it less important. If you, or someone else you care about, were in that 1%, you would likely want them to be able to access to abortion.
The utilitarian argument is not the only basis in determining the ethical implications of abortion.
There are many reasons why utilitarianism may be flawed.
Utilitarian evaluations are relevant to many people, particularly utilitarians, whether they are the sole basis for every person's opinion or not.
Many argue that morality is not subjective when it comes to causing harm. If abortion causes harm to the fetus then the context does not matter.
No one can dictate a certain morality to another person nor can they demand how another person acts or how they should feel based on their individual morals.
Different people can hold different opinions of ethics, however that does not mean they are all equally correct and does not prove the subjectivity of ethical rules.

Ethics can vary from culture to culture, with some slavery, for example. However, the underlying moral standards of right and wrong do not vary, even if a culture chooses not to base its ethics in those moral principles.
There is no indication to believe that there are moral standards of right and wrong.
There is large debate about the existence of objective morality.
Under this thinking you could do whatever you want, whenever you want, and for whatever reason you want, no matter how many people get hurt, killed, or taken advantage of in the process.

Most relevant definitions of "subjective" state that something is subjective if different people can hold different opinions on the matter. If people can hold different opinions on whether or not abortion is immoral or unethical, it is subjective according to those definitions.

Morality by definition is not subjective. Preferences are entirely subjective and are neither right or wrong, they are just different tastes. Morality assumes "right" is not "wrong" and vice versa. Whenever a person assumes something is right they are assuming it is not wrong thus automatically proving a standard.
A fetus develops during the gestational period such that it does gain self-awareness and consciousness. Therefore it can still be argued it should qualify for personhood status while still in utero.
The fetal stage of human development is about 8-40 weeks from conception. Cortical function is present by 30 weeks.
A fetus develops the capacity for self-awareness and consciousness around the beginning of the second trimester. Thus, it should be regarded as having the unalienable right to life.

While it is true that a fetus develops sentience in utero, it does not have sentience from the moment of conception. Therefore, a fetus should not be considered a person prior to the development of sentience which roughly coincides with the beginning of the 2nd trimester.

Many non-human animals have cognitive capacities well beyond those of a fetus. These capacities are not typically taken to be sufficient for a right to life in the case of animals so it is unclear why they ought to be sufficient in the case of fetuses.
It's very clear why cognitive capacities are sufficient for a fetus and not sufficient for an animal. A fetus is a human and an animal is not. Human rights are not the same as animal rights.
For example, "right to life" does not exist among animal rights. One can euthanize their dog.
Not being self aware, conscious, and able to feel pain does not stop one from being a person with rights.
People in a coma or people in an alive but unconscious state aren't disqualified as human or having less rights simply because they are not aware.
It is definitely wrong to end the life of a person in a coma if the coma is reversible, and the person probably has a long life ahead of them.
The claim that consciousness is necessary for rights confuses the source of rights with the effect of that source. The root of rights is human nature.
Consciousness is an effect not a cause of human nature. Nor is evidence of consciousness the only evidence of human nature.
It is always considered wrong to end the life of a healthy human being. It is not always considered wrong to end the life of someone who is in a coma.
In many cases, the assisted death of someone is performed with the intent of ending suffering (often of patients with a terminal illness).
This is not relevant to fetal personhood because the baby is not suffering, and therefore the justification for taking a life in that case doesn't apply here.
People who can't feel pain qualify as people.
The referenced material is very far from being the unanimous definition of personhood.
Personhood is a variable concept depending on one's personal philosophy, and so should not be used as a benchmark for assigning value to human life.
Roe v Wade determined that, in the US, a fetus is not legally recognised as a person.
Numerous attempts have been made to pass personhood laws in the US, which would classify zygotes, embryos and fetuses as persons, but such attempts have had little success.
This continuity begins with sperm and egg, which would make masturbation similar to abortion.

Masturbation generally does not include both eggs and sperms present simultaneously, and by most definitions does not include fertilization. There is a distinct beginning of continuity with fertilization.
There is a big jump between sperm cells and a baby with formed organs inside a mothers womb not yet able to live on its own.
There is no scientific basis to give personhood to the gametes of any of the two sexes. Neither of them is a totipotent cell, with the potentiality to become human beings on their own.

A sperm plus an egg would give rise to such a totipotent cell. If such a cell is of moral value, it stands to reason that what gives rise to it is also of moral value. In that case, destroying or preventing the development of a sperm plus egg would be as immoral as destroying or preventing the development of a zygote or fetus.
That they have had little success doesn't mean that they are wrong.
The right to life is fundamental, but life begins at independent viability.
A fetus's right to life does not imply the right to use the mother's body to sustain its life.

In Judith Jarvis Thomson's famous violinist example, she argues that people would be outraged if upon waking up they found themselves plugged to an ailing violinist and told that in order for the violinist to remain alive, they must remain plugged to them for the next nine months.
Such an experiment demonstrates how abortion does not violate a fetus' right to life. Rather, it just deprives the fetus of the use of the pregnant person's body.
The violinist example can only be used to justify abortion in the case of rape, because in the example, you did nothing that could have led to you being attached to the violinist.

The violinist example is not analogous because withdrawing support is very different from directly killing. In that example, the person did not create the violinist's dependency on their body whereas the parents are responsible for the creation of a fetus, thereby creating an obligation to provide due care.

This assumes that withdrawing support is different from direct killing. This distinction is unclear at best, since both cases involve a decision (terminate life) causally connected to a consequence (termination of life).

It is an assumption that all biological parents choose to create life, which confers obligations. Many pregnancies are accidental, and even if they weren't, you should be allowed to change your mind after experiencing the realities of pregnancy.
In the violinist example the violinist is a complete stranger, while in a pregnancy the baby is the mother's own child.

A mother who fails to provide for her own child's basic needs such as food and water is guilty of child neglect, whereas someone who passes a stranger on the street begging for food and doesn't give them anything is not guilty of a crime. This intuitively supports the idea that a person's obligations towards their own child is greater than that towards a stranger.
One plausibly has duties (moral or legal) to persons under one's charge, like children. However, it is not at all clear that one has duties to an unwanted fetus.
A mother has duties to her two-year-old son, regardless of whether the child is "wanted". Therefore it is plausible that the fetus being "unwanted" doesn't take away her duties towards it.

When a fetus is able to exist independently from the mother's body they can be considered to be independent living beings. During pregnancy the fetus is specifically reliant on the mother to maintain their life, which is no longer the case once they are born, making them more independent.
The mother's body naturally sends nutrients to the fetus. That she might not consciously approve of this doesn't mean the fetus is violating her rights by accepting the nutrients offered.

Independent viability is a moveable target, so irrelevant to the ethics of life and value. No one is 'viable' in an environment contrary to the needs of survival, such as a child in the ocean or an adult in the vacuum of space.

Future technology may be able to develop an artificial womb or incubation method as an alternative to pregnancy. This means what is "viable" is partially dependent upon current technology and doesn't ultimately answer the question.
Viability is a weak argument for determining the right to life. A human on life-support isn't viable, but we still believe they are are human beings with rights.
Newborns (and most people who are under 18) cannot live independently, but they are still persons.
This obscures the order in which personhood is first attained. A human on life-support attains viability before losing it in this example.
The law does not necessarily always reflect what should be the case. Morally, one can still argue that a fetus should be recognised as a person.
In 1857, the U.S. Supreme Court declared in Dred Scott v. Sandford that blacks were 'not persons' and therefore didn't have the rights of people.
If laws were always moral, there wouldn't be any reason to ask for a change in the law.

Morals are a set of rules that individuals live by, thus it cannot be suggested that people with different morals are somehow incorrect or wrong. Women should have the right to choose what happens to their body and to live by the morals they choose for themselves.

If a society polices for murder, theft, or other crimes considered immoral, then that society finds it ethically acceptable to determine what is a crime, create laws to prohibit that crime, and then police to enforce the law.
These laws may change over time as the society reevaluates and changes, but the fundamental ethics of the society hold that it may create laws based in moral principles and then enforce them.

Saying that “women should always have the right to choose” is a moral judgment, that according to your argument, can not be judged as “correct” or “right.” All laws are codifications of moral judgments, and there are some acts that are universally considered immoral, such as the taking of an innocent human life.
A number of scientific advancements mean that the Roe v Wade decision should be reconsidered.
Since Roe v Wade, significant advancements have been made in genomics allowing us to see that babies in the womb are genetically humans, beginning at conception.
There is no generally accepted definition of 'personhood', but this argument hinges on one particular definition.

All arguments for or against abortion are dependent upon a specific definition of personhood. At its roots, it is personhood itself that is being debated. Thus it is not valid to dispute one argument but not another on this basis.
The definitions of "personhood" in which the fetus is a person in a philosophically meaningful sense are philosophically inferior to those in which a fetus is not a person.

If a fetus is defined as a person, it may follow that other biological entities are persons, including bacteria, plants or some animals. As those don't meet the intuitive or conventional notion of persons, such a definition is inferior to one that meets the intuitive notion.
While fetuses may not be considered people, the law has still given them rights in certain situations.
Some states in the US have held women criminally liable for using illegal drugs that harm the fetus, therefore recognising that the fetus does have some right to not be harmed.
The Unborn Victims of Violence Act recognises fetuses as legal victims if they are injured or killed as the result of a federal crime of violence.
Fetal protection policies were used to bar women from working in roles that could cause harm to embryos or fetuses.
The US Supreme Court determined that such policies were a form of sexual discrimination which violated the Civil Rights Act.
Laws can and do change and thus cannot stand as evidence for or against what should be the case.

This is a matter of public vote, not moral or scientific fact. So it’s somewhat cyclical to offer this as a pro-choice argument. The point at which we deem something alive is probably the most important point in the discussion of whether that thing should receive rights.

The public should not arbitrarily decide via a vote what is, and is not a life. They are often not qualified to do so. Scientists are qualified to do so, their expertise should not be dismissed in order to appease uninformed citizens.

The biological definition of "life" serves a scientific purpose, and does not bestow any philosophical value on an object unless people decide that it does. Even if the deciding factor is deeming the fetus "alive", it will be a separate debate from what biologists consider useful to label as "alive".
Tadpoles are the beginning of the frog lifecycle. They are still not frogs any more than caterpillars are butterflies or blastocysts are human.
They would still have the same DNA as a frog, which makes them a frog.

The science of embryology directly falsifies this claim. Natural, developmental changes in the outward appearance of a living organism - even dramatic changes like with the butterfly - do not produce a different kind of organism. According to modern embryology, a zygote is a distinct, living, and whole human being.
Actually frogspawn is the beginning of the frog lifecycle. And by this kind of thinking, you could argue that a child shouldn't be considered human because it hasn't grown into an adult yet.

A living human organism develops through stages, but is not biologically less or more a human organism at any stage. Some of the various stages are zygote, blastula, embryo, fetus, neonate, infant, adolescent, and adult.
After 4-6 weeks of fetal development, the fetus develops a heartbeat. A heartbeat is an indication of life so the fetus should get legal protections as a human with the right to life.

If we claim a person to be dead when their heart stops beating, life should begin when their heart starts beating. Claiming the fetus is not independently survivable at that point doesn't matter. Many people are kept alive by the assistance of machinery and technology.

CPR happens when a heart stops beating and doesn't stop without reason, until then only a doctor can pronounce someone dead. This is because even people with experience and knowledge can't call someone else dead because their heart stops beating.
A beginning and end are different. A person dying when their heart stops doesn't mean the heart beating is when it starts.
This would imply that a heart beating was a necessary condition for human personhood, not that it was a sufficient condition.
A heartbeat is not enough to define life. The neural system is far more relevant to draw a line between an alive and conscious human and a bunch of worthless cells.
Given scientists and philosophers haven't reached a consensus on the difference between a human and a fetus in terms of the brain, using the brain as the sole criteria is an unnecessary ethical risk.

While a fetus doesn't have brain and heart activity, all its cells are working together for the survival of the system as a whole. This is an important component of cellular organization, a central benchmark of biological life.
We do not consider it murder to "pull the plug" on someone who is brain dead, even if their heart is beating.

A heartbeat is a mechanical function like any other. Machines can be designed with systems which are analogous to heartbeats. The heartbeat is "an indication of life" insofar as a person without a heartbeat is generally either dead or likely to die imminently, not such that an object having a "heartbeat" makes it a living being.
Pulling the plug on a brain dead person occurs when medical professionals agree there is very little to no chance at life. This is not always the case for "voluntarily" aborted fetuses.
Some people do in fact always consider it wrong to end the life of someone who is in a coma.  As long as the patient isn't brain dead (i.e. "dead") then it's wrong to pull the plug.
Though what seems like a heartbeat happens after twenty days, the heart isn't developed until twenty weeks.

Fetuses are yet to become citizens of the state since they are unborn and therefore have no rights or protection under common law.

Citizenship is irrelevant to the legality and morality of the act. Non-citizens enjoy the protection of the law just as much as citizens do. It is not legal to kill a non-citizen any more than it is to kill a citizen (p. 5).
A fetus is not self aware, conscious, or able to feel pain.
It is not until 28-30 weeks into the pregnancy that the fetus starts to feel pain. A woman should have the right to an abortion, as long as it's before that time.
Fetuses can feel pain well before that.

A study concludes that from the 15th week of gestation onward, “the fetus is extremely sensitive to painful stimuli," and this should be considered when performing invasive medical procedures on the fetus to prevent suffering.
The support for this argument is a single testimony provided in an article written by an organization prejudiced against abortion.
Killing people is still considered unethical even if the victim doesn't feel pain.
Ethics and morality are subjective and can vary from society to society or even from person to person.
As with all acts, the morality of abortion varies with the person's context.

In an instance where the pregnant woman's life is at risk and the fetus would not survive on it's own, utilitarianism argues that an abortion would be more ethical than letting both the woman and the fetus die.
The basis of utilitarianism argumentation would be that the overall good of saving the woman's life outweighs any unethical implications of abortions.
The utilitarian argument is not the only basis in determining the ethical implications of abortion.
There are many reasons why utilitarianism may be flawed.
Utilitarian evaluations are relevant to many people, particularly utilitarians, whether they are the sole basis for every person's opinion or not.

Having an abortion for medical reasons makes up less than 1% of all abortions, even lower when the "life of the mother" is in jeopardy. The utilitarian justification for abortion is therefore very, very small.
Statistics regarding the number of abortions due to endangerment of mother's life back this up. Florida, 2015: 0.065%. UK,1968-2011: 0.006%. U.S. estimate: 1%.
It is reasonable to give priority to the mother over the child in extreme cases. However, this does not make voluntary abortions acceptable.

"Less than 1% of all abortions" could be misleading because if between 1970 and 2014, there were "44.5 million legal induced abortions", then there could be 445k abortions that fall in this category. That would be a significant impact to a lot of people.
The number of times something happens doesn't always make it less important. If you, or someone else you care about, were in that 1%, you would likely want them to be able to access to abortion.
Abortion would still need to be legal for those cases, as adoption would not solve the issue at hand.
Many argue that morality is not subjective when it comes to causing harm. If abortion causes harm to the fetus then the context does not matter.
No one can dictate a certain morality to another person nor can they demand how another person acts or how they should feel based on their individual morals.

Ethics can vary from culture to culture, with some slavery, for example. However, the underlying moral standards of right and wrong do not vary, even if a culture chooses not to base its ethics in those moral principles.
There is no indication to believe that there are moral standards of right and wrong.
There is large debate about the existence of objective morality.
Under this thinking you could do whatever you want, whenever you want, and for whatever reason you want, no matter how many people get hurt, killed, or taken advantage of in the process.

Most relevant definitions of "subjective" state that something is subjective if different people can hold different opinions on the matter. If people can hold different opinions on whether or not abortion is immoral or unethical, it is subjective according to those definitions.

Morality by definition is not subjective. Preferences are entirely subjective and are neither right or wrong, they are just different tastes. Morality assumes "right" is not "wrong" and vice versa. Whenever a person assumes something is right they are assuming it is not wrong thus automatically proving a standard.
A fetus develops during the gestational period such that it does gain self-awareness and consciousness. Therefore it can still be argued it should qualify for personhood status while still in utero.
A fetus develops the capacity for self-awareness and consciousness around the beginning of the second trimester. Thus, it should be regarded as having the unalienable right to life.

While it is true that a fetus develops sentience in utero, it does not have sentience from the moment of conception. Therefore, a fetus should not be considered a person prior to the development of sentience which roughly coincides with the beginning of the 2nd trimester.
The fetal stage of human development is about 8-40 weeks from conception. Cortical function is present by 30 weeks.

Many non-human animals have cognitive capacities well beyond those of a fetus. These capacities are not typically taken to be sufficient for a right to life in the case of animals so it is unclear why they ought to be sufficient in the case of fetuses.
It's very clear why cognitive capacities are sufficient for a fetus and not sufficient for an animal. A fetus is a human and an animal is not. Human rights are not the same as animal rights.
For example, "right to life" does not exist among animal rights. One can euthanize their dog.

Not being self aware, conscious, and able to feel pain does not stop one from being a person with rights.
People in a coma or people in an alive but unconscious state aren't disqualified as human or having less rights simply because they are not aware.
The claim that consciousness is necessary for rights confuses the source of rights with the effect of that source. The root of rights is human nature.
Consciousness is an effect not a cause of human nature. Nor is evidence of consciousness the only evidence of human nature.
It is definitely wrong to end the life of a person in a coma if the coma is reversible, and the person probably has a long life ahead of them.
It is always considered wrong to end the life of a healthy human being. It is not always considered wrong to end the life of someone who is in a coma.

This is why brain death is generally the medical definition of death.
Being a human being does not require a functional brain because anencephalic infants do not have a functional brain, but they are still human beings.
