Morals are a set of rules that individuals live by, thus it cannot be suggested that people with different morals are somehow incorrect or wrong. Women should have the right to choose what happens to their body and to live by the morals they choose for themselves.

If a society polices for murder, theft, or other crimes considered immoral, then that society finds it ethically acceptable to determine what is a crime, create laws to prohibit that crime, and then police to enforce the law.
These laws may change over time as the society reevaluates and changes, but the fundamental ethics of the society hold that it may create laws based in moral principles and then enforce them.

Saying that “women should always have the right to choose” is a moral judgment, that according to your argument, can not be judged as “correct” or “right.” All laws are codifications of moral judgments, and there are some acts that are universally considered immoral, such as the taking of an innocent human life.
Skin cells are as human as a zygote, gall bladders are as human as a fetus. In neither case is it immoral to destroy the former, thus simply being human is an insufficient criterion.
Skin cells and gall bladders could develop into a full human (via cloning or transformation into induced pluripotent stem cells), just as a fetus could.
A fetus is human in that it has human DNA: skin cells and gall bladders have human DNA.
A gall bladder is part of a human, and so are skin cells. However, a zygote is a whole human, which makes it immoral to destroy.
Fetuses are not whole humans. If they were, they would be able to live outside the womb without the mother's help. The earlier in the development of a fetus, the less whole it is.
Viability is a weak argument for determining the right to life. A human on life-support isn't viable, but we still believe they are are human beings with rights.
Newborns (and most people who are under 18) cannot live independently, but they are still persons.
This obscures the order in which personhood is first attained. A human on life-support attains viability before losing it in this example.
It is, in fact, immoral to destroy someone else's gall bladder without their permission.
The right to life should be considered fundamental and absolute.
The right to life is fundamental because it is crucial in order to allow people to access their other rights and make any future choices.
The right to life is enshrined in Article 3 of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.

The fact that the right to life is enshrined in the Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR) doesn't make the right to life absolute. The UDHR says nothing about the right to life of animals or (hypothetical) aliens. The first article makes it clear that such rights begin at birth (p. 120).
The Universal Declaration of Human Rights is not a legally binding instrument.
The legal ramifications of a document have no bearing on the moral applicability of its implications.
Governments do not do everything they can to ensure that people remain alive for as long as possible, which they should if the right to life is absolute and fundamental.
Governments do not put all of their money into healthcare and medical research to allow people to live as long as possible.
Governments do not make it a requirement of people to donate organs even though this would mean being able to save many people's lives.
Governments do not do many other things that are good for the population. What governments do or fail to do shouldn't be used as an argument for the morality of anything.
The 'right to life' is not the same as 'the right to be kept alive for as long as possible'. It only means that a human has the right to live, and should not be killed by another human being.
The government made murder illegal because it violates the right to life. The same should go for abortion.
Capital punishment is still legal in a number of countries, and in a number of US states. This shows that at times the state condones the ending of life, meaning the right is not absolute.
Capital punishment is a specific circumstance where people have committed a heinous crime and therefore have a number of their rights restricted or taken away.

The removal of rights after due process is never the case with abortion. The gestating human has either done nothing to warrant the removal of their rights, or does not even possess such rights. Capital punishment has no bearing on the abortion discussion.
Capital punishment is a penalty meant for someone who committed serious crimes. The fetus' life should not be terminated since he/she did not commit any crime.

Capital punishment is an act of self-defense, imparted only by the State, and is an act of last resort, i.e. the prisoner is still a danger to society. It is not a statement on the value or right to life of the one being executed.
Capital punishment protects the right to life by establishing consequences for murderers.
Even though a fetus cannot necessarily exist outside a mother's body immediately, it is a living being with the potential to live a full life and therefore should be protected.
Allowing abortions means allowing people to end potential lives, removing all future possibilities of this being existing and having their own desires and wants.
Abortion takes away any future experiences from a baby that was meant to be born.

The idea that someone is 'meant to do something' or that something is 'meant to happen' is an appeal to an unsubstantiated authority, and thus in effect is really just an attempt to impose the will of one person onto another.
The suggestion that a baby was "meant to be born" relies on a belief in a higher power which has specific intentions. It is not clear that this is the case.

Abortions have the same ethical ramifications as abstinence and contraception - all three result in the lack of a life that could have existed. If abortion is unethical, so is avoiding impregnating and avoiding being impregnated at any time.
If we draw the line at conception, then all hormone-based contraceptive methods are abortions.
Hormone-based contraceptive methods can thicken the lining of the uterus, preventing attachment of the fertilized egg.
If life truly were to begin at conception, IVF would also be highly immoral as multiple eggs are fertilized in vitro, and often not all of them used.
IVF could be considered even more immoral, since whole teams of people spend lots of time effort and money deliberately pursuing treatments that end up leaving multiple embryos to die in the freezer.
Some pro-lifers such as Catholics oppose both abortion and IVF, so it is unlikely that they can be convinced to abandon the pro-life position.
Not all hormonal contraceptives are abortive. Many prevent ovulation, which means an egg is never released to be fertilized.
One could plausibly hold that abortion and hormone-based contraceptions are both immoral, so this claim doesn't address the pro-life position completely.
One could reject abortion and accept hormonal contraception if they regard the intention of the woman as morally relevant.

In the case of hormonal contraception, if a zygote does fail to implant this was not intended by the woman. Instead, she intended to prevent the meeting of sperm and egg to form the zygote in the first place. In abortion, however, the destruction of the baby is fully intended.
This is a fallacy of equivocation. In the event of an abortion, the life of the fetus has already begun, so there exists something to be destroyed.

Given that abstinence and contraception are merely inaction resulting in a lack of life, whereas abortion is an intentional action which leads the destruction of life, the latter is moral by comparison.
Contraception is not inaction, as it requires very specific actions to be taken.

The action/inaction distinction is a matter of ease - it is hard to sacrifice your hard-earned money even when you know it's the right thing to do, but easy not to go out and rob a charity. An abortion and a healthy pregnancy both require effort and active intent.

Neither abortion advocates nor pro-life advocates claim that there is an ethical mandate to bring all theoretically possible life into the world, so this interpretation of the ethical ramifications is an example of an appeal to extremes fallacy.

It's philosophically untenable for a third party to make an argument for just one of another person's potential futures, against that person's own interest. Almost anything could conceivably prevent almost anything else in the future; it's called the butterfly effect.
Even if the fetus is not "human" in the sense that it looks, walks, and talks like us, the fetus has potentiality. Left untouched, it will develop naturally into a person.
Leaving the fetus in the womb is not the same as leaving it "untouched". At multiple stages the fetus requires assistance from the mother's body or it will cease to develop and quickly die.
There is no guarantee that a fetus 'left untouched' would develop into a baby. Regrettably, miscarriages may occur.
Miscarriages are remarkably common and as many as 1 in 4 pregnancies end in miscarriage.
There is a significant difference between a miscarriage and an abortion.
Miscarriages are not caused by people in most cases. Abortion is done on purpose.
It is also true, unfortunately, that not all infants develop into adults. However, this does not justify labeling infants as nonpersons.
Until a gestation in progress is entirely outsourceable, like parenting is, it is not ethical to force involuntary servitude (ex: forced gestation) on a person because they are pregnant.

Vague potential cannot be the foundation of ethically significant decisions. A fetus also has the potential to live a short life filled with suffering, but we do not therefore suggest that all fetuses should be aborted.
This is a far less common outcome for babies in modern society than a long life, so it should not be assumed that any particular baby will have to undergo this.
The potential to have a full life does not guarantee that the life should be protected.

A person dying of kidney failure still has the potential for full life, but that does not grant them the right to risk the life of someone else by demanding a kidney transplant. In the same way, a fetus with the potential for full life cannot demand the use of the mother's body because pregnancy risks the mother's life.
The number of pregnancies that are life-threatening to the mother is extremely small.
Some conceptions fail because the fertilised egg never implants in the uterus. Human reproduction is just too inefficient to consider conception the beginning of even a potential life.

Conception, if scientifically defined as when a sperm and egg merge, takes place at any time from moments after male ejaculation until days later. Therefore, the concept that life begins at conception is nebulous at best and has little practical value for determining the beginning of a life.
Every living human's life ultimately began at conception. It makes no moral difference that some were ended sooner than others.

Life begins before conception. Sperm and ova are both alive. Romanticising the next step is illogical, as an embryo has little more potential to become someone than its separate parts had to become that same someone.
The spermatozoon and the oocyte (which fuse at conception to produce the zygote) are both alive. Thus life does not begin at conception.
Sperm and ova don't contain a full human's DNA separately. They need to be combined for a life to occur and for it to start growing into a human.
Human cloning is inevitable. At that point perhaps one source of DNA may suffice.
A sperm or ovum in its natural environment by itself will never become an adult human being; a zygote in its natural environment (a womb) can.
A zygote lacks a mind or perception. It does not matter if it is destroyed as long as it's with the consent of the mother. The potential to be a person is not equivalent to personhood.
The right to life is fundamental, but life begins at independent viability.
A fetus's right to life does not imply the right to use the mother's body to sustain its life.

When a fetus is able to exist independently from the mother's body they can be considered to be independent living beings. During pregnancy the fetus is specifically reliant on the mother to maintain their life, which is no longer the case once they are born, making them more independent.

In Judith Jarvis Thomson's famous violinist example, she argues that people would be outraged if upon waking up they found themselves plugged to an ailing violinist and told that in order for the violinist to remain alive, they must remain plugged to them for the next nine months.
Such an experiment demonstrates how abortion does not violate a fetus' right to life. Rather, it just deprives the fetus of the use of the pregnant person's body.
In the violinist example the violinist is a complete stranger, while in a pregnancy the baby is the mother's own child.

A mother who fails to provide for her own child's basic needs such as food and water is guilty of child neglect, whereas someone who passes a stranger on the street begging for food and doesn't give them anything is not guilty of a crime. This intuitively supports the idea that a person's obligations towards their own child is greater than that towards a stranger.
One plausibly has duties (moral or legal) to persons under one's charge, like children. However, it is not at all clear that one has duties to an unwanted fetus.
A mother has duties to her two-year-old son, regardless of whether the child is "wanted". Therefore it is plausible that the fetus being "unwanted" doesn't take away her duties towards it.
The violinist example can only be used to justify abortion in the case of rape, because in the example, you did nothing that could have led to you being attached to the violinist.

The violinist example is not analogous because withdrawing support is very different from directly killing. In that example, the person did not create the violinist's dependency on their body whereas the parents are responsible for the creation of a fetus, thereby creating an obligation to provide due care.

It is an assumption that all biological parents choose to create life, which confers obligations. Many pregnancies are accidental, and even if they weren't, you should be allowed to change your mind after experiencing the realities of pregnancy.

This assumes that withdrawing support is different from direct killing. This distinction is unclear at best, since both cases involve a decision (terminate life) causally connected to a consequence (termination of life).
The mother's body naturally sends nutrients to the fetus. That she might not consciously approve of this doesn't mean the fetus is violating her rights by accepting the nutrients offered.

Independent viability is a moveable target, so irrelevant to the ethics of life and value. No one is 'viable' in an environment contrary to the needs of survival, such as a child in the ocean or an adult in the vacuum of space.

Future technology may be able to develop an artificial womb or incubation method as an alternative to pregnancy. This means what is "viable" is partially dependent upon current technology and doesn't ultimately answer the question.
Viability is a weak argument for determining the right to life. A human on life-support isn't viable, but we still believe they are are human beings with rights.
Newborns (and most people who are under 18) cannot live independently, but they are still persons.
This obscures the order in which personhood is first attained. A human on life-support attains viability before losing it in this example.

The bodily autonomy of the fetus cannot be exercised because the will of the fetus cannot be known. That is, the fetus did not choose to be conceived. In that sense, the will of the fetus is just as likely to be violated in allowing its birth as in preventing it.
It is not true that "the will of the fetus is just as likely to be violated in allowing its birth as in preventing it" because statistically, most people who are born do not wish to be killed.
Only 9.2% of people ever experience suicidal ideation. This would probably be even lower if their option for death was one of the grisly methods involved in modern abortions.
Even if the fetus is a life, so is the mother. It is not clear that the right to life of a fetus necessarily trumps the right to bodily autonomy and self-preservation of the mother.

It is impossible to give a fetus 'equal rights' to the person carrying it. To claim that a fetus has an inviolable right to life is to say that it should be born regardless of circumstances, even if it seriously harms or kills the pregnant person.
Pregnancy symptoms can be severe and can involve life-threatening illnesses.
By definition, preventing abortion is torture. It punishes people for getting pregnant and forces them to give birth, all with a painful process.

Preventing abortion is not torture because actual torturers intend to inflict as much pain as possible on their victim and do not care about preserving human life, whereas pro-lifers are motivated by a desire to preserve human life, and also want to minimize the pain of pregnancy, childhood, and motherhood as much as possible. This is why they set up pregnancy resource centers to help women with unplanned pregnancies.
The health risks associated with a late abortion, are still less than the health risks associated with childbirth.
The hormonal and psychological shifts that occur during pregnancy put some women at an increased risk for mental illnesses, such as anxiety and depression.
Many women suffer from postpartum depression.
This is especially true in women who miscarry or in cases where the child is stillborn or has such a severe illness that it does not live for very long.

Depression after a miscarriage is usually most severe immediately after a pregnancy is lost. In one study, researchers discovered that after a year, women who had a miscarriage experienced rates of depression similar to those of women who didn’t have a miscarriage.
If a stillborn child or child that doesn't live for very long causes an increased risk of depression, then a child terminated in the womb would cause an even greater increase of risk of depression.

A study in the British Journal of Psychiatry found that women had a 37% higher risk of depression due to abortion compared to term birth. Stillbirth only has an 11% higher depression risk compared to term birth and it declines over time.

A miscarriage or stillborn baby is 100% dead (or non-living, depending on your view). If a mother fears for this outcome of their fetus, an abortion should also be feared because it confirms the death of the fetus. However, if the mother chooses not to have an abortion, the chances of the fetus surviving birth is non-zero.

There are cases where an abortion would be for the best even when the mother wants the child. This ban on abortion caused a mother serious psychological trauma by forcing her to feel her baby die in her for 3 days before being able to get a stillborn removed. Abortion in this case was the more humane option.
Society doesn't give depressed mothers the right to kill their infants or toddlers, so depression in and of itself is not an ethically justifiable reason to terminate life.

Postpartum depression affects 1 in 10 women, and is especially common in circumstances where the mother has a history of mental health problems. As depression is a serious and potentially life-threatening mental illness, these concerns can be a fair and legitimate factor when deciding whether to terminate an unwanted pregnancy.

While postpartum depression is common, the risk of self-harm comes from postpartum psychosis which is more rare. The postpartum suicide rate is less than 2 out of every 100,000 births. This is around the same risk as the mother dying from hemorrhage/placenta previa or eclampsia/pre-eclampsia.
Screening questionnaires, doctor follow-ups, and local resources greatly mitigate the risks of a women with postpartum psychosis committing suicide.

As society does not consider it morally permissible to allow mothers with known depression to kill their infant children, it would be even less morally permissible for a mother to kill an unborn child on the sole basis of potential future depression.
Many women who have abortions suffer a lifetime of depression and guilt as a result of terminating their pregnancies.

US researchers followed nearly 1,000 women who sought abortions nationwide for five years and found that those who had abortions did not experience more depression, anxiety, low self-esteem or dissatisfaction with life than those who were denied it.
95% of women who have had abortions do not regret their decision to terminate their pregnancies.
This 95% statistic is based on one study and biased reporting. Here is an article that shows 40 to 60% have negative reactions and 31% regret it.
Post-abortion syndrome has not been validated as a discrete psychiatric condition and is not recognized.
Depression is only a possible post-birth complication, not a guaranteed outcome.
Abortion causes the death of the fetus and death is more severe than anxiety or depression.

Restrictions on abortion services have been associated with increased infant and increased maternal mortality risk, which is more severe for both the mother and the birthed infant than an early first trimester abortion.
Child-birth is a dangerous and complicated medical procedure.

Even under ideal medical supervision each case can be potentially lethal to women. No one can be forced to undergo a risky medical procedure. Some women know that they will have complications. They can't be forced to risk their lives.
There are many common types of pregnancy complications.
In the US, 6 to 8% of pregnancies are high risk.

Even in developed nations, with world class health care systems, there is still a non-zero chance that individuals may die whilst giving birth. Women who are under the age of 15, older mothers, and women from lower income groups are particularly at risk.
As long as the risk of death during childbirth remains non-zero, it is unethical to force a person to continue their pregnancy.
In the U.S., approximately two to three women die in childbirth every day.

The “non-zero” argument suggests that, since we cannot attain a perfect situation (e.g. perfect birthing surgery), we may as well accept the potential consequences of bad situations (e.g. miscarriages) and not act to reduce those consequences. This implies that we should give up anything where perfection is unlikely to be attained.
For example, we may as well give up cars because the chances of having an accident is non-zero.
Nobody is claiming that childbirth in general isn't worth it due to risk of death. The key point here is allowing the woman to have the choice to bear that risk, or not to.
Most births aren't that complicated. Child birth has been ongoing since time immemorial.
Abortions have also been ongoing for centuries, if not millennia.
The Bruce effect is a type of abortion that exists in nature.
Fathers-to-be experience hormonal changes during pregnancy as well.
Fathers will still never feel the physical effects of childbirth in the way mothers do.
The small hormonal changes in men during pregnancy cannot be compared to the drastic changes women's bodies have to go through.
In these instances, it is possible to make exceptions to the law without outright making abortion a legal choice.

Trying to sort out the exceptions from the general rule (especially if this is an exception wherein all other abortion is illegal and not merely, say, 3rd trimester or post-viability abortions) would require extensive, unjustified government invasion into the woman's privacy.
Enforcing laws and drawing lines between what is legal and illegal is often a long process, prone to mistakes. Abortion is a time-delicate matter which cannot be postponed for next hearing.

If the unborn child poses a risk to the life of the mother the aim is to deliver the child, not to kill it. This might pose an additional risk to the child if delivered very early but is not an abortion, e.g. aiming to kill the baby.
In these instances, it is possible to make exceptions to the law without outright making abortion a legal choice.
Enforcing laws and drawing lines between what is legal and illegal is often a long process, prone to mistakes. Abortion is a time-delicate matter which cannot be postponed for next hearing.

Trying to sort out the exceptions from the general rule (especially if this is an exception wherein all other abortion is illegal and not merely, say, 3rd trimester or post-viability abortions) would require extensive, unjustified government invasion into the woman's privacy.
Women have a right to bodily autonomy and should ultimately be able to make choices about what happens to their bodies.
Denial of abortion rights is simply another way in which the patriarchy attempts to control what women do with their own bodies.
Women's ability to carry children and give birth does not mean she should be limited or restricted by her reproductive functions in ways which men are not.
By removing the ability of women to choose to opt out of pregnancies they do not desire, women become far more controlled by their reproductive systems.

In patriarchal societies, women have experienced a great deal of violence that involves assaulting their bodies through domestic violence or sexual assault. Giving women control over their bodies is an important step in acknowledging that they, not men, should be able to determine what happens to them.
Sexual assault and domestic violence are unfortunate. In these cases, the perpetrator should be given a fair trial and have to deal with appropriate punishments determined by the court.
Being forced into the life of a traumatized mother who didn't want to have it would punish the "baby" even more while further traumatizing the mother.

If opposition to abortion is motivated by attempts to control women, it is unclear why pro life groups also oppose human cloning and embryonic stem cell research which have nothing specific to do with women.

There is very little percentage difference between men (42%) and women (38%) who believe abortion should be illegal in all or most cases, or in the percentage of women (59%) and men (55%) who believe it should be legal in all/most cases. If the patriarchy is a factor at all, it is not a significant one.
Elizabeth Blackwell, an early feminist and the first woman to get a medical degree, was also strongly pro-life. It is unlikely that she was a part of the patriarchy.

Something being part of the patriarchy does not mean that it is believed or executed only or mostly by men. Slut-shaming is a clear example of this, being both an element of the patriarchal system and done by a vast number of women as well as men.

There is a difference in the amount of men and women in political positions that ultimately end up creating the laws surrounding these issues. The patriarchy isn't just ground-level, it's about a larger system of inherent bias, including positions of power (aka the government).

Abortion is an instrument of the patriarchy. It's a way men can use women as objects of sexual pleasure and escape the responsibilities of fatherhood. Sometimes women may decide to get an abortion because of pressure or threats from the father.
A survey of 1000 women found 74% felt pressured by others while 30% chose abortion because they feared losing their man.

A survey of 1209 abortion patients found that fewer than 1% had abortions primarily because someone else insisted. Thus, in the majority of cases women would have their choice taken away by abortion being illegal, not legal.
The fact many prominent pro-life groups such as Live Action, Students for Life, and PLAGAL are lead by women makes it difficult to argue that the entire movement is controlled by the patriarchy.
Women can also uphold the patriarchy.
Internalized misogyny is prevalent among women, on account of patriarchal structures, and can lead to anti-abortion attitudes.
Women may uphold the patriarchy when they get some sort of material benefit from doing so, but it is unclear what this benefit might be in the case of holding pro-life views.
If women do not have the right to choose an abortion, someone else should not decide they have more of a right to deny them one.

By the same argument, an aborted child also has to live (or rather die) with their mother's decision and it's likely they would be far more offended themselves were they given the chance to be part of the discussion concerning their termination.

A judge in a court of law has every right to prescribe the necessary course of action, whether they would or wouldn't like to be on the receiving end of the same judgement. Their obligation is to the law, not to the defendant.
Women have a legal claim to a right to abortion.
Banning abortion betrays the role of government as preserving liberty as stated in the Declaration of Independence.
Individual freedom is the basis of the US constitution. There is no right more fundamental then the choices we make about our own bodies. If we do not have that right, then none of the others matter.
In the US, the Supreme Court decided that bodily autonomy was an unenumerated right that could be inferred from privacy protections in the constitution.
Legally, you can't do anything you want to with your body. For example, prostitution is illegal in many places.

Prohibitions against prostitution do not prevent one from having sex with someone else; but prohibits the consideration (in the contractual sense) of money or property. Thus, the criminality of prostitution is a commercial law, not a restriction on bodily autonomy.
Women have a moral right to bodily autonomy.
Decisions which largely impact on an individual and their body should ultimately be made by that individual rather than by the state.
The state allows individuals to make decisions even if they could harm other people.
For example, people are not required to donate blood or put their life at risk to protect others even if it would save other people.
The state has the power to prevent actions that harm others, not to compel actions to prevent harm. The two are not the same.
The law cannot compel someone to jump in and save a drowning man, but it can intervene if a person take actions to drown another person.

You are not required to put your life at risk to protect your child but you are required by law to take care of it. This argument supports the case for abortion where there is a high likelihood of death to the mother, but does not support a general right to choose abortion.

We do not give people the right to use other's people's body to use or sustain them without express and ongoing consent. If women want to remove that consent, they should be able to do so by having an abortion.

In Judith Jarvis Thomson's famous violinist example, she argues that people would be outraged if upon waking up they found themselves plugged to an ailing violinist and told that in order for the violinist to remain alive, they must remain plugged to them for the next nine months.
Such an experiment demonstrates how abortion does not violate a fetus' right to life. Rather, it just deprives the fetus of the use of the pregnant person's body.

The violinist example is not analogous because withdrawing support is very different from directly killing. In that example, the person did not create the violinist's dependency on their body whereas the parents are responsible for the creation of a fetus, thereby creating an obligation to provide due care.

It is an assumption that all biological parents choose to create life, which confers obligations. Many pregnancies are accidental, and even if they weren't, you should be allowed to change your mind after experiencing the realities of pregnancy.

This assumes that withdrawing support is different from direct killing. This distinction is unclear at best, since both cases involve a decision (terminate life) causally connected to a consequence (termination of life).
The violinist example can only be used to justify abortion in the case of rape, because in the example, you did nothing that could have led to you being attached to the violinist.
In the violinist example the violinist is a complete stranger, while in a pregnancy the baby is the mother's own child.

A mother who fails to provide for her own child's basic needs such as food and water is guilty of child neglect, whereas someone who passes a stranger on the street begging for food and doesn't give them anything is not guilty of a crime. This intuitively supports the idea that a person's obligations towards their own child is greater than that towards a stranger.

The mother's body naturally sends nutrients to the fetus. That she might not consciously approve of this doesn't mean the fetus is violating her rights by accepting the nutrients offered.
Many women do not become pregnant by choice. It is wrong to force these women to remain pregnant when they do not want to be.
Some pregnancies are the result of an act of violence like rape.
Raped women often don't have an option to use birth control.
There are contraceptive methods, such as the morning after pill, which can be used to guard against the possibility of becoming pregnant following cases of rape.

In cases of non consensual sex, the person who was forced by someone to have sexual intercourse has no moral obligation to not kill the unborn-person. Every harm caused to the unborn is the responsibility of the person who forced the other to have sexual intercourse.
You cannot transfer responsibility for harm to another person. The person responsible for the abortion is the person going to the clinic.
In the rare case of pregnancy due to rape, terminating the life of the unborn child will not correct the horror done to the woman, it will simply pass on the act of force to an innocent party.
Termination of the unborn child's life is not done to mitigate the effects of the crime on one's past, it is to minimize its effects on one's future.
This is especially true for young teenagers that were raped by pedophiles; forcing a child into motherhood, on top of dealing with the sexual violence, would be unnecessarily cruel.
Often healthcare professionals are not educated on how to deal with women who have become pregnant on account of rape.
In these instances, it is possible to make exceptions to the law without outright making abortion a legal choice.

Trying to sort out the exceptions from the general rule (especially if this is an exception wherein all other abortion is illegal and not merely, say, 3rd trimester or post-viability abortions) would require extensive, unjustified government invasion into the woman's privacy.
Enforcing laws and drawing lines between what is legal and illegal is often a long process, prone to mistakes. Abortion is a time-delicate matter which cannot be postponed for next hearing.
Some schools provide such inadequate sex education that some people may not realise sex leads to pregnancy.

A report found evidence abstinence-only curricula promoting irresponsible, high-risk teenage behavior by keeping teens uneducated with regard to reproductive knowledge instead of giving them the tools to make educated decisions regarding their reproductive health [37].
Then the solution is better education, not abortion. To justify an act simply because it remedies a negative event based on a lack of education is simply lazy.
It is unreasonable to be satisfied with poor education, but this leaves justification for it though a workaround.
The reason for abortion doesn't need to be "justified" if you do not see it as immoral. Poor education would merely be an explanation, and abortion the remedy.
Woman face too many difficulties getting their tubes tied to be able to prevent pregnancies.
Women consent to the risk of becoming pregnant whenever they choose to have sex.
It is possible for women to research contraception and the likelihood of pregnancy before they have sex, such that they are aware of the risks.
The internet has made such information widely available, even in conservative communities.
This would assume that conservative communities are open to the use of contraception and the bodily autonomy of women which is not the case.
When women use contraception it is clear they are trying to avoid pregnancy and therefore should not be held responsible for the outcome.
Use of contraception indicates consent to pregnancy has explicitly not been given.
No form of contraception is 100% effective.
Even used perfectly, condoms are only effective 98% of the time.
Planned Parenthood states that the pill is only about 91% effective because it is difficult to maintain perfect use.
If the pill is used perfectly, it is 99% effective.
Abstinence is always effective.
An abstinent woman can still be raped and become pregnant.
Abstinence is only 100% effective if used perfectly. The "typical use" effectiveness of abstinence as a contraceptive is not 100%.

It is unreasonable to expect people to remain abstinent forever. There are people who may want to have sex lives but do not ever want to have children. For them there is no fail proof form of contraception.

Humans are designed to find pleasure in sexual relations. Sex is more than just for reproduction; it is also a bonding mechanism between life-long partners. Therefore an abstinence only method is an unreasonable burden for a person to bear.

The primary role of sexual relations is reproduction. This is true in all species that reproduce by mating. The pleasure and bonding effect of a sexual relation is subservient to its purpose as a reproduction mechanism.
People have sex for pleasure and bonding effects more often than for reproduction across all ages.

Contraceptives advertise that they are not 100% effective. Even though these devices or drugs decrease the likelihood of pregnancy they don't negate the responsibility for the risk of the action chosen.
Sterilization procedures (hysterectomy, vasectomies) are almost 100% effective.

Male vasectomies are both reversible and do not stop your body from producing sperm. It is one of the most highly-effective birth control measures while still maintaining the possibility of having children in the future.
Although it is rare, vasectomy failure is still a possibility. In the first year after vasectomy, 15 to 20 of every 10,000 couples experience a pregnancy.
Sterilisation is a near-permanent procedure - it is not a suitable contraceptive option for people who want to have children in the future.
There is a small risk that female sterilisation will not work - blocked tubes can rejoin any time after the operation.
On average, one woman in 200 will become pregnant after undergoing a female sterilisation procedure.
Low-income women often lack sexual education and even if they do have this information, they sometimes lack the resources to buy contraceptives.
Contraception is not cheap or widely available in many developing countries around the world, even in some parts of the US and Europe.

A small pack of condoms will cost you around 5€. Less developed countries may find contraception somewhat more expensive, however abortion procedures in those parts of the world are far more dangerous and costly, so prevention and abstinence are still the better options. To increase effectiveness and safety, one should compliment usage of contraception with proper sexual responsibility.

According to WHO, only 43% of women of reproductive age in less developed countries use modern contraceptive methods, and a wide gap in use is seen between the highest and lowest wealth quintiles (52% versus 35%, respectively).
Social norms can stop people from being able to avail of contraception.
A lack of sex education in many conservative regions means that couples are often ill equipped to properly use contraceptives such as condoms.
